INSERT INTO msxdb_company VALUES ('717','Softmen','','0','KR','Softmen','A very early independent developer (Kim Gicheol), Softmen delivered some technically impressive programs for the Samsung SPC-1000. Softmen not only produced games, but also educational software. In 1987, the team left its mark by being the first Korean company ever to deliver a home entertainment game for the Japanese market, but was never heard of again, afterwards. 
INSERT INTO msxdb_company VALUES ('718','Space','','0','KR','','','','','0','','','','3934','3','0','0','2010-06-21','2010-06-21','5','5');
INSERT INTO msxdb_company VALUES ('719','Open','','0','KR','','At the end of the Saehan Sangsa / Zemina alliance, Kim Eulsuk formed his own independent development studio, employing several former Zemina programmers and freelancers like Koo Eunjoong, Lee Sanghun, Lee Kyuhwan and Lee Sangyoun (although the latter two didn''t stay with the company for long). A year later, they became a second party developer for Daou Infosys, a partnership that produced more 8-bit console games than anyone else at the time. Other products were cheat modules for the Mega Drive and Super Famicom (the former was also capable of transferring data between the console and a PC).
INSERT INTO msxdb_company VALUES ('720','SIECO','','0','KR','','SIECO published MSX and Mega Drive games from at least 1991. Two years later, they started to put out a number of Master System games, mostly developed by Open. From late 1994, SIECO''s properties were picked up by a company called Gameline, who also converted the games to the Mega Drive and released several multi game carts.
